dataIdInfo.idPurp: This dataset summarizes the exceedance and compliance information for community and non-transient non-community (specifically schools and day cares) public drinking water systems that are regulated by the State Water Resources Control Board (State Water Board) or Local Primacy Agency (LPA).
dataIdInfo.idAbs: This dataset summarizes the exceedance and compliance information for community and non-transient non-community (specifically schools and day cares) public drinking water systems that are regulated by the State Water Resources Control Board (State Water Board) or Local Primacy Agency (LPA). It is updated on a monthly basis. Please note that the State Water Board's regulatory authority does not include water systems that are defined as "state small water systems", "local state small water systems" or private domestic wells. For more information about the data see the Human Right to Water Portal at https://www.waterboards.ca.gov/water_issues/programs/hr2w/or the map service description at http://gispublic.waterboards.ca.gov/arcgis/rest/services/HR2W/Exceedance_Compliance/MapServer.
dataIdInfo.idCredit: California State Water Resources Control Board, Division of Drinking Water

attrdomv.udom: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.

attr.attrdef: The county where the public water system is located.
Population of the county where the public water system is located.
The city in which the public water system is located.
The zipcode for the public water system location.

Compliance Status describes the compliance status of each public water system with the primary drinking water standards. In compliance means that the system is achieving compliance with the federal/state primary drinking water standards. Out of compliance means that the system is currently in violation of one or more federal/federal primary drinking water standard. Return to compliance means that the water system has had one or more violation(s) of a federal/state primary drinking water standard since January 1, 2012, but is now in compliance with all federal/state primary drinking water standards.
attr.attrdefs: California State Water Resources Control Board, Division of Drinking Water
